[Prior to the availability of varicella vaccine, there were approximately 4 million cases of varicella a year in the USA. Though usually a mild disease in healthy children, an estimated 150 000 to 200 000 people developed complications, about 11 000 people required hospitalization and 100 people died each year from varicella. Although the viral infection tends to be more severe in adolescents and adults than in young children, complications can occur in children, especially those who are immunocompromised. Routine immunization in children would prevent this by minimizing varicella in non-immunocompromised children, who would potentially function as a reservoir for the immunodeficient pediatric cohort. A similar logic was used for routine rubella immunization regardless of gender, as although only pregnant females can transmit the rubella infection to a fetus and produce congenital rubella syndrome (CRS), immune males produce an extra safety net to prevent CRS. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3336005,100.]
